---
The Archive Schism was the civil conflict within the Great Pyramid when competing record houses produced irreconcilable versions of succession.
The proximate cause: the Iseth Reach's drying reduced the Pyramid's internal water supply, forcing the Embalmer Houses (requiring large water volumes) into competition with the Seal College (requiring purified water for containment rituals).
Each faction maintained its own succession records; when the records contradicted each other, no neutral authority existed to adjudicate.
Three simultaneous failures: the Schism in record legitimacy, military ritualization as war sancta generals eclipsed civil authority, and Seal Fatigue as containment systems required escalating sacrifice.
The Schism produced the current state of the Great Pyramid's internal records: multiple parallel versions of historical documents, each authenticated by its producing house, each contradicting others on succession and authority.
Regent-line militarization of funerary priesthoods was the Schism's most lasting consequence: civil shrine staff became armed toll enforcers — the first Jackal Synod cadres.
Surviving Seal College practitioners who fled became the diaspora origin of the cleric tradition.
Surviving Embalmer House practitioners became the origin lineage of the necromancer tradition's practical knowledge base.
The Schism produced no institutional winner: both factions were weakened; the Pyramid sealed itself before a resolution could be imposed.
The Schism's legacy is institutional: wherever competing institutions control overlapping records, the conditions for schism recur.
The Archive Schism is the reason the Great Pyramid's records cannot be used as definitive historical authority: every document's provenance traces through one faction's record-keeping.

