Kiess's charter doctrine cites the Archive Schism as the canonical case of two institutions holding exclusive control over contradictory records with no third-party arbitration. Kiess's three-power design was partly a response: no institution should hold exclusive control over records that affect other institutions; external review prevents Schism conditions. The Schism's lesson: record systems that cannot be externally verified will eventually diverge from external reality and from each other. Kiess position: the Schism was not caused by bad actors — it was caused by a governance design that created competition where cooperation was required and then provided no resolution mechanism.

